results.description:
Wild grapes or Riverbank grapes (Vitis riparia)
Found along a backyard fence across Ontario and Quebec. Can be found all over the world. Leaves and ripe fruits are edible in the fall. 
Not to be confused with menispermun (moon seed grapes)

results.description: Woody vine. Presumably more than 5 feet long. Leaves alternate lobed and toothed. Lobes shallow, going about only 1/4 of the way through the leaf. Teeth up ti .25 cm. Tendrils present opposite leaves except every third leaf. Small hairs on leaf edges and on backs of leaves at veins. Small, green, unripe fruits present.

Dixon Prairie, 
Chicago Botanic Garden. 

Vine, creeping on the ground. Woody stems. Opposite coarsely toothed leaves, leaves hairless.

Not rare but not common.

No fruit or flowers present.

comments.body: What do I look for as a difference between the two?

good question.  I have not seen vulpina often enough to be able to give you a good answer. But in general it should not have the pointy teeth or strong 3-lobed appearance.  I have thoroughly inventoried the plants of Gorge and know that riverbank and summer are the only two I have seen . . so I guess I am cheating : )

comments.body: really?  you think even with the leaf?  These leaves are throwing me this week.  And it was so tart.  Ok you know these things better than me. And frost looked so on and the taste was so tart. Ok riparia  it is and i thought i nailed this one :)

That it did.  I'm still trying to get Plants of Pennsylvania like you suggested so I mostly do pictures and info from the internet which isn't always reliable so I defer to you great teacher ;) so far you haven't led me wrong

This looks just like V riparia to me, and although I am not very familiar with V vulpina, the key says V vulpina should 1) barely have lobes, 2) have rounded teeth, and 3) have grapes without the whitish film.
Make sure you understood my last comment.  Those were qualities of V vulpina.  V riparia has lobed leaves, distinct teeth, and a whitish film on the fruits (like I see in the photo).
I understood just didn't type well sorry.  I meant didn't.
